Since they popped q first (since stack.pop() gives the top element first?), Wait, in Java's stack, the first pop is the top element. Let me see:

In the Java code:

s.push(x.charAt(i));

then, while (s.size() >1):

   p = s.pop();

   q = s.pop();

So p is the top element, q is the next one below it. So the order is q is below p in the stack. So when they are pushed back, it's s.push(q), then s.push(p). So the stack is restored to the state before the two pops. So in the else case, the stack is back to the same as before the two pops, so the loop breaks.
